    {
      "kind": 1,
      "languageId": "markdown",
      "value": "---\n\n## Part 4: Fetch the `Aircraft` Counts Using Different Filters\n\nNow that you have the `Base`'s information displayed, you'll add real-time metrics on the aircraft.\n\nYou need to know with a single glance: how many aircraft are ready? In maintenance? Grounded?\n\nIn this section, you'll implement advanced filtering to calculate these numbers on-the-fly and display them in Key Performance Indicator (KPI) tiles:\n- Combine multiple filters using logical operators (`&&`).\n- Make several API calls for different data slices.\n- Render dashboard metrics.",
      "output": [],
      "executionSummary": {}
    },
    {
      "kind": 1,
      "languageId": "markdown",
      "value": "<div class=\"alert alert-info\" style=\"color: black;\">\n<h4><b>Activity 4.1: Retrieve, Filter, and Count the Aircraft Data</b></h4>\n\nStart this activity by navigating to <a href=\"../ui/c3/src/components/CRUDMethods/AircraftCRUD.ts\" style=\"color: blue;\">/ui/c3/src/components/CRUDMethods/AircraftCRUD.ts</a>.\n\n**Instructions**:\n\n1. Open the file `AircraftCRUD.ts`.\n2. Complete `TODO 4.1` in the function `fetchAircraftCountWithFilter`:\n\n    i. Create a combined filter that chains together the `baseId` and additional filters using the intersection (`&&`) operation. Reference the ERD to find the correct field on the `Aircraft` Type that `baseId` will match.\n\n    ii. Make a POST request to the endpoint `api/8/Aircraft/fetchCount`.\n\n    - Use the `fetch()` API with method `POST`.\n    - Include headers: `{ 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }`.\n    - Pass a request body that filters the `Aircraft` by both `Base` ID and the additional filter.\n\n    iii. Parse the response as JSON\n    \n    iv. Return the parsed data\n</div>",
      "output": [],
      "executionSummary": {}
    },
    {
      "kind": 1,
      "languageId": "markdown",
      "value": "Next, call this function with four different filters to get the number of aircraft that have a status of `\"Ready\", \"In Maintenance\", \"Grounded\", and \"Deployed\"`.",
      "output": [],
      "executionSummary": {}
    },
    {
      "kind": 1,
      "languageId": "markdown",
      "value": "<div class=\"alert alert-info\" style=\"color: black;\">\n<h4><b>Activity 4.2: Trigger the API Call</b></h4>\n\nStart this activity by navigating to <a href=\"../ui/c3/src/customInstances/Aircraft.BaseDetailsPage.tsx\" style=\"color: blue;\">/ui/c3/src/customInstances/Aircraft.BaseDetailsPage.tsx</a>.\n\n**Instructions**:\n\n1. Open the file `Aircraft.BaseDetailsPage.tsx`.\n2. Import the function `fetchAircraftCountWithFilter` from `AircraftCRUD.ts` in `TODO 4.2.1`.\n3. In `TODO 4.2.2`, inside the `useEffect` hook, call the function `fetchAircraftCountWithFilter` four times, once for each status: \n    - `\"Ready\"`\n    - `\"In Maintenance\"`\n    - `\"Grounded\"`\n    - `\"Deployed\"`\n4. Store each of these values in the respective state variables: \n    - `numReadyAircraft`\n    - `numInMaintenanceAircraft`\n    - `numGroundedAircraft`\n    - `numDeployedAircraft`\n</div>",
      "output": [],
      "executionSummary": {}
    },
    {
      "kind": 1,
      "languageId": "markdown",
      "value": "With the aircraft counts now stored in state, the final step is to display them using pre-built KPI components.",
